# 📄 User.java — README

**Package:** `models`
**Type:** `abstract class`
**Project:** SolveStack – Open Innovation Collaboration Platform

---

## 📌 What Is This File?

`User.java` is the **root base class** of the entire SolveStack system. Every person who uses the platform — whether they are a Company, Developer, Evaluator, or Admin — is ultimately a `User`. This file defines the shared identity, authentication, and profile management behaviour that all roles inherit.

Because it is declared `abstract`, you can never create a plain `User` object directly. You must always work through one of its concrete subclasses.

---

## 🎯 Purpose & Responsibility

| Responsibility | How It Is Handled |
|---|---|
| Store user identity | Private fields: `userId`, `username`, `email` |
| Authenticate users | `login(String password)` method |
| End user sessions | `logout()` method |
| Show role dashboard | `viewDashboard()` — delegates to subclass |
| Allow profile edits | `updateProfile(...)` method |
| Enforce role contracts | Three `abstract` methods subclasses must implement |

---

## 🧱 OOP Concepts Applied

### 🔒 Encapsulation
All nine fields in this class are declared `private`. This means no external class can directly read or write a user's password, ban status, or login state. Access is strictly controlled:

- **Public getters** allow reading non-sensitive data (`getUsername()`, `getEmail()`, etc.)
- **Protected setters** (`setVerified()`, `setBanned()`) restrict mutation to subclasses and trusted internal code only
- **`passwordHash`** has no getter at all — it can never be read once stored, only compared internally

This prevents accidental or malicious tampering with a user's credentials or account state from outside the `models` package.

---

### 🔷 Abstraction
Three methods are declared `abstract`, meaning they have no body in `User.java`. They exist purely as a **contract** — a guarantee that every subclass will provide its own implementation:

```java
public abstract String getRole();
protected abstract void displayRoleDashboard();
public abstract void onAccountRemoved();
```

- `getRole()` — Each role returns its own label: `"Company"`, `"Developer"`, etc.
- `displayRoleDashboard()` — Each role shows different dashboard content
- `onAccountRemoved()` — Each role performs its own cleanup when deleted

If a subclass forgets to implement even one of these, the Java compiler will throw an error. This is abstraction enforcing correctness at compile time.

---

### 🧬 Inheritance
`User.java` is designed to be **extended, not instantiated**. The four subclasses of the system all inherit from it:

```
User (abstract)
 ├── Company.java
 ├── Developer.java
 ├── Evaluator.java
 └── Admin.java
```

Every subclass automatically gets `login()`, `logout()`, `updateProfile()`, and `viewDashboard()` without rewriting them. This follows the **DRY principle** (Don't Repeat Yourself).

---

### 🔀 Polymorphism
`viewDashboard()` in `User.java` is a **concrete method** that calls `displayRoleDashboard()` internally. Since `displayRoleDashboard()` is abstract and overridden differently in each subclass, the same `viewDashboard()` call produces a completely different result depending on which subclass object you're working with.

```java
User u1 = new Company(...);
User u2 = new Developer(...);

u1.viewDashboard(); // Shows company challenges, submission counts
u2.viewDashboard(); // Shows developer's submissions and tracked challenges
```

This is the **Template Method Pattern** — the skeleton of the algorithm lives in `User`, the variable parts live in each subclass.

---

## 🔐 Password Security

Passwords are **never stored as plain text**. The moment a password is passed into the constructor or `updateProfile()`, it is immediately passed through `hashPassword()` and the original string is discarded.

```java
this.passwordHash = hashPassword(password);
```

In the current prototype, `hashPassword()` uses a simple polynomial rolling hash for demonstration. In **Phase 2**, this will be replaced with **BCrypt** — an industry-standard adaptive hashing algorithm.

